The EMAG (Export MAGazine) is a lightweight 30-round 5.56x45 NATO polymer magazine that features a number of aesthetic and functional changes from the PMAG®. While EMAG remains 100% compatible with the AR15/M16 platform, its unique geometry is optimized for foreign-made weapons such as the British SA-80 (L85A1/A2, L86A1/A2, L22A1, L98A1/A2), HK 416, M27 IAR, and others.

EMAG features the same pop-off Impact/Dust Cover as the PMAG GEN M2 to prevent dirt and debris intrusion and protect the feedlips from potential impact damage during transit and storage. When not in use, the Impact/Dust Cover can be stored on the magazine's floorplate to prevent possible loss.

For easy and accurate identification of loaded round count via the large, dual-sided MagLevel windows, the stainless steel magazine spring is coated with mil-spec black oxide and the indicator coil painted with a high visibility orange color. Numerical indicators are added to the body to identify 5, 15, and 25 loaded rounds.

postcontent:
I have a Diamondback DB380 for sale or trade.
It's in flawless condition and fires great. I have put 50 rounds of assorted defense ammo through it with no problems.

This LIKE NEW pistol comes with two 6 round mags and a carry case. and a DeSantis Superfly posket holster.

It's a straight shooter; I'm selling it because my daily carry is already small enough to carry anywhere and I don't need two different calibers.

The DB380 differs from most small modern pocket autos. Most have a hammer action, but the DB380 is striker-fired. It has a positive mechanical firing pin block for safety, and the twin action bars and striker action result in a very smooth and relatively light trigger pull. The square profile slide and disassembly system give the DB380 a Glock-like appearance. (It looks like a baby Glock.) The DB380 has a locked-breech action, and a striker that is set by the retraction of the slide. The trigger is made of steel, and has a smooth face for comfortable operation. The magazine holds six rounds for a total loaded capacity of seven, and the magazine catch is made of stainless steel. Another nice feature of the DB380 are the sights: I can actually see the sights on this pistol well enough for them to be useful." -- Jeff at Gunblast

title: For Sale:  Spikes Tactical AR74 5.45x39 Upper Lothar Walther Melonite Barrel
postcontent:
This upper is a limited run specifically designed to chew through cheap surplus AK74 ammunition. Make yourself an AR74 by dropping this onto your existing standard AR15 lower and save at least $500 on every 1000 rounds of ammo. 1080 round sealed cans of surplus AK74 ammo are still only about $160. It is in stock right this moment at Wideners for $180 (yes that is the price for 1080 rounds!). The AK74 round in this caliber is by FAR the cheapest military spec'd ammo to acquire now, has nearly the same ballistics as 5.56 (it actually performs even better out of shorter barrel lengths), and is more destructive on impact. For those of you that are not familiar with the AK74 or 5.45x39 caliber ammunition, see below for an interesting read. For sale is one brand new Spikes Tactical complete 5.45x39 caliber 16" Upper Receiver Group. This Corrosion Resistant Upper features a Melonite finish inside and out. Features include a top quality Lothar Walther Barrel with Nickel Boron (NiB) treated M4 Extension, Melonite coated F-marked FSB, Melonite coated Gas Tube, Stainless Roll Pin, and Melonite coated A2 Flash Hider. Built to handle the dirtiest surplus ammo with no ill effects and still be a breeze to clean. Price is $800 for this brand new in box special limited production Spikes Tactical 5.45x39 Corrosion Resistant Upper without bcg and charging handle, or $1100 with bcg and charging handle included. It takes the same bolt carrier and charging handle as any other AR15 in .223 / 5.56, only the bolt is different and must be for 5.45x34 so you may use your existing AR15 bolt carrier in it as long as you swap the bolt with one designed for 5.45x39. 

During the 1960's the Soviet military made the decision to convert their assault weapons from 7.62mm to a reduced caliber of higher velocity. This was based in part on studies of the American made M-16 during the Vietnam conflict. They felt that the United States may know something they didn't and decided to follow their example. This did not sit well with Mikhail Kalashnikov who felt that the M-43 7.62x39 cartridge was sufficient for all modern battlefield needs. Even so he began work on a new weapon to chamber the smaller cartridge.
The task of designing the cartridge fell to a group led by Viktor Sabelnikov. Other prominent designers on the team were Lidiya Bulavskaya, Boris Semin, Mikhail Fedorov, Petr Sazonov, and Petr Korolev. Their task was to develop a 5.45mm low impulse cartridge that would be more accurate than the cartridge currently used in the AKM assault rifles.
The result was a small caliber bullet of very high velocity. The bullet also has good sectional density and a fairly flat trajectory. Despite being lighter in weight than its predecessor, the 5.45mm cartridge retained the same lethality as the older round. It can penetrate a 5mm steel sheet at 350 meters, not bad for a 53 grain bullet.
Another feature that contributes to the lethality of the cartridge is that it becomes unstable when it strikes an object. This means that although it flies perfectly well through the air, it tumbles violently after striking a target - creating a larger wound channel when compared to a normal bullet. This was accomplished by leaving a hollow space at the front of the bullet which makes the round imbalanced on impact with flesh or wood.

REVIEW: This caliber is just great fun to shoot. We tested it in a Romanian rifle with eight 30 round magazines. Recoil is SO LIGHT and it functioned 100% of the time. No malfuntions at all. Overall, this is SUPER GOOD SURPLUS.
